That's the thing, though. There are plenty of settings where the world is shit and half the people are irredeemable assholes, but that simple doesn't do it. It takes a certain self-awareness, but that doesn't have to boil down to the setting mocking itself. I've found that settings that poke fun at themselves can really shoot themselves in the foot when it comes to storytelling. After all, when the setting doesn't take itself seriously, then why should I? And it takes a boatload of warranted confidence to sell something ridiculous with a straight face. One of the first things Berserk gets out of the way is that Guts' sword is ridiculous, but no-one thinks it's funny.

Another one that comes to mind is the Witcher. I've only played 3 (and haven't read the books), but on paper it sounds like peak edge. Dark, faux Medieval setting where non-humans are persecuted by a benighted and frightened population. And then there's this half-monster hero with superhuman powers, with flowing locks of an unusual color, who bones all these femme fatales. And of course people fear him, or even hate him. It's part of the entire package. But the Witchers really are callous, powerful people who do whatever the fuck they want but are perfectly human in their capacity to get shit disastrously wrong.

Edgy is fairly well defined, as being on the edge of the norm for popular culture. But popular culture shifts while we continue to take ques from the past. We're talking about Berserk, but that comic started in the late 80's/early 90's. Guts is a contemporary of Captain Picard. But that kind of reminds me of the writing of Andy McNab, which is pretty much exactly what you say: Shocking stuff for the sake of being shocking. I ended up reading two books by the fucker (they were gifts), and it was a chore. You have no emotional connection to the characters being killed, and you start to expect it. Everyone around the main character dies. And if he cares about them, they're guaranteed to die. Man, Andy McNab has issues. That man needs help. Mostly just solid writing advice, but maybe he isn't all there.

I think internal consistency is the most important thing, as it is in all fiction. The villains doing random raping or killing can fit them perfectly, but you have to ask what the point is. For instance, the Mongols apparently liked to rape women in the town square of conquered cities, making everyone watch. It's a submission thing. But they didn't do it randomly. Same with the Imperial Japanese army. Lots of rape and torture, but it wasn't random. They wouldn't rape and torture when they were on leave back home. They were caring, loving family members and upstanding citizens back home.

I don't bring that up because the world would be poorer without the first kind. You need to cut your teeth somewhere. Maybe you never do more than that, but people create for all kinds of reasons.
Even the types that write My Immortal-tier stuff dared to see things past the idea stage.
To paraphrase AC/DC: for those about to create, we salute you
